Thanks <@U061HDV96> .  English is not my native language, still struggling :smile:
I heard you like typos so I put at typo in my typo report

Ok so reading your article I have to disagree with using them for an activity reference.

1) as stated already you should basically never use asynctask, that’s a given.
2) updating your activity directly from a thread callback is the real issue, you should have a disconnect between the thread callback and your view (activity in this case) that allows your activity to shut down gracefully and your thread to presumably shut down gracefully or finish as needed ie if it cached and notified you dont want to end it you just dont want the view update. MVP is an answer here but its not a requirement to have the same effect, if your view is ‘null’ because the activity has recycled the callback shouldn’t be concerned with that.
This isn’t to say that WeakReferences are not useful just that I believe in the context you are using them in the article is not a good practice as you are tightly coupling your work to your view
<@U055GGAHS> you're thinking too much of it. It's just a general example.
And it's something good to keep in mind when you can't use 3rd party libs or don't have MVP in place.

Thanks for the Feedback <@U055GGAHS> . Using an AsyncTask or whatever is a mean to show how an object can refer another one. The point I want to stay there is how an object cannot be collected due to being references from another.

<@U061HDV96> I would normally agree, an example is just an example but this is on the GDE group page so I feel like it should avoid showing the suggestion at all to use it for activities as people :heart: to copy paste code.

If we need to make a 100% right example we would need to implement a MVP pattern and the article would loose its purpose. I want to showcase in 20 lines an scenario. Is about finding a compromise between fully correctness and being practical
you could make the same example by not using an activity
I trust the readers will be able to extract the lesson
<@U055GGAHS> ahh I didn't know it was on the GDE page. I'm not much of a Medium user
<@U08GFT5V5> I just closed docker in the middle of a build forgetting there was a build going on
I was like "shit shit, nononono don't start over"
I start up again it and it just continues :heart:
Never said it was poorly written software
Damn multidex... is so damn slow
<@U055GGAHS> luckily it's easy to add IdlingResources to Espresso like they do with AsyncTasks
